<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Acamptopappus</i> <i>sphaerocephalus</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>acanthocarpa</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>cooperi</i> and/or <i>Pleuraphis</i> <i>rigida</i> may be dominant in the shrub, subshrub and/or herbaceous layer with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Echinocereus</i> <i>engelmannii</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Krameria</i> <i>erecta</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>schidigera</i>. The herb layer is usually present and may also include <i>Amsinckia</i> <i>tessellata</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>rubens</i>, <i>Erodium</i> <i>cicutarium</i> and <i>Sphaeralcea</i> <i>ambigua</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is open to intermittent with seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Cylindropuntia acanthocarpa, Ericameria cooperi, Acamptopappus sphaeracephala, </i>and/or a diverse mixture of seral shrubs dominant in stands while <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>may be dominant or co-dominant with other grasses including <i>Muhlenbergia porteri </i>in the herbaceous layer (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ericameria cooperi</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer (Klein and Keeler-Wolf 2014, VegCAMP 2014b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Upper alluvial fans, mid-elevation flats, and lower to upper hillslopes. Soils vary from coarse sands to loams.  </div>
</div>

        
