<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cylindropuntia acanthocarpa </i>is an open to spreading cactus with cylindric stem joints; the plants grow to 1.5 m in height. The stem joints have clusters of spines that are covered in papery sheaths. Its stems can break off and re-root, readily growing new plants.   The yellowish flowers form spiny fruits, and its seeds are not very fertile (Anderson 2000).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>is a highly branched, perennial grass that has a bushlike appearance. Its coarse, rigid culms reach 100 cm in length, and they may be erect or decumbent. Seed production is low and seedling establishment rare. It reproduces primarily by rhizomes and tillers. It is the most drought-tolerant of the <i>Pleuraphis </i>species (Matthews 2000). This warm-season and drought-tolerant grass, is rarely found in the western Mojave Desert where summer rainfall is negligible. Much of the botanical literature uses the name <i>Hilaria rigida</i>.<br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance occur at mid to upper elevations in a matrix with other semi-desert vegetation. They appear to have experienced disturbance from grazing, clearing, and/or fire, whereby shrubs may be sparse or lower in cover and include disturbance-tolerant species. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
