    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag-h, Aj-m). Stands occur in the western Mojave (VegCamp 2015a) and are known from Mojave National Preserve in the Ivanpah, Providence Mountains, Lanfair Valley, and the Piute Range (Evens et al. 2014).  Stands also possibly occur in the Sacramento Mountains and the Chemehuevi Valley and Mountains region (CCH 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-i). Stands of <i>Ericameria cooperi</i> are mapped at Fish Slough (VegCamp 2014b). However, more data collection is needed to determine if these stands are better related to stands of <i>Ephedra nevadensis </i>and <i>Lycium andersonii </i>or to this alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stand of <i>Ericameria cooperi </i>are recorded near Tehachapi Pass (VegCamp 2015a). However, more data collection is needed to determine if these stands are better related to stands of <i>Ephedra nevadensis </i>or to this alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bp). Stands occur in the very eastern part of the section such as in the Santa Rosa & San Jacinto Mountains National Monument.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Livestock grazing, altered fire frequencies, or other disturbances can have a beneficial effect and increase stands of this alliance at the detriment to other types such as <i>Coleogyne ramosissima, Ephedra nevadensis, Grayia spinosa, Yucca schidigera, </i>and <i>Yucca brevifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

